def build_model_1_1():
    model = models.Sequential()
    model.add(layers.Flatten())

    model.add(layers.Dense(750, activation='relu'))
    model.add(layers.Dense(375, activation='relu'))
    model.add(layers.Dense(200, activation='relu'))
    model.add(layers.Dense(45, activation='relu'))

    model.add(layers.Dense(10, activation='softmax'))
    model.compile(optimizer='adagrad',loss='categorical_crossentropy',metrics=['accuracy'])
    return model

Answer 1.2, Preprocess (2p)¶

  • Convert images to greyscale, other preprocessing optional.
    • Input shape should be (32,32,1)
  • Explain design decisions. Is it better? Why (not)?
    • Color information is likely not so useful for classification. Greyscale makes the network smaller, less parameters to learn, less likely to overfit.
All we changed was to perform the rgb2gray function on X_train and X_val, since color doesn't change the value of the number in the image and only makes analyzing the image more complex we can just leave it out. This should make recognizing patterns easier for the network.  (length: 275)

I tried learning rates of 1,0.1,0.01 and 0.001 but with every batch size and epoch size, 0.01 was much better. The epoch size of 30 also seemed optimal. Adding regularizers seemed to always be much better immediately bumping accuracy from around 70 to 80. Batch size of 10 and 50 are too small, I tried small deviations of the batch size like 20, 25 and 25 seemed to be a little bit better than 30.  (length: 400)

Answer 2.1, ConvNet (7p)¶

  • Build a sequential ConvNet, get at least 90% accuracy.
    • Conv2D layers, input shape (32,32,1)
    • Consider using blocks of Conv2D layers with maxpooling in between
    • Use zero-padding in Conv2D layers because the images are small
    • At least one dense hidden layer and dense output layer (sigmoid)
    • Consider adding batch normalization, dropout
    • Consider small dropout rates in beginning, larger dropout rates later in network
    • Consider other optimizers and tuning learning rate, momentum,...
  • Explain what you did and why (800 chars). Is it working well?

I started off with a convulation network based on the one from the lab, since that had a similar use case. I then added the pyramid type net from question 1, which seemed to improve the accuracy by about 4%. THen by trying some different epoch settings I tried 3,5,10,20 30, 40, 50 and it seemed that 40 was the sweetspot. def build_model_2_1():
  model = models.Sequential()
  model.add(layers.Conv2D(32, (3, 3), activation='relu', input_shape=(32, 32, 3)))
  model.add(layers.MaxPooling2D((2, 2)))
  model.add(layers.Conv2D(64, (3, 3), activation='relu'))
  model.add(layers.MaxPooling2D((2, 2)))
  model.add(layers.Conv2D(64, (3, 3), activation='relu'))
  
  model.add(layers.Flatten())
  model.add(layers.Dense(750, kernel_regularizer=regularizers.l2(0.001), activation='relu'))
  model.add(layers.Dense(375, kernel_regularizer=regularizers.l2(0.001), activation='relu'))
  model.add(layers.Dense(200, kernel_regularizer=regularizers.l2(0.001), activation='relu'))
  model.add(layers.Dense(45, kernel_regularizer=regularizers.l2(0.001), activation='relu'))

  model.add(layers.Dense(10, kernel_regularizer=regularizers.l2(0.0001), activation='softmax'))
  model.compile(optimizer='rmsprop',
                loss='categorical_crossentropy',
                metrics=['accuracy'])
  return model

Answer 2.2, Data Augmentation (3p)¶

  • Augment the preprocessed training data.
    • Use small variations (small shifts up-down, left-right) of flips becasue the images are small
    • Large shifts and rotations distort the image too much
  • Explain what you did and why. Discuss the performance of the model.
For some reason with the generator, the model works much worse, even without any augmentations, the accuracy is around 17-18%.I only tried to make changes that were logical, for example a horizontal flip of a 2 would look like a 5, so I mostly tried to stay away from such changes. I mostly found that any drastic changes warped the images too much, so the only way to up the accuracy was with small changes all around 0.1  (length: 424)

Answer 3.3, Class activation map (4p)¶

  • Show a class activation map for your last convolutional layer
  • Superimpose the activation map over the image, or plot side by side
    • Should make sense, detect interesting regions to classify the number
def plot_activation_map():
  x = np.expand_dims(test_image, axis=0)
  preds = model_2_2.predict(x)
  with tf.GradientTape() as tape:
    last_conv_layer = model_2_2.get_layer('conv2d_14')
    iterate = tf.keras.models.Model([model_2_2.inputs], [model_2_2.output, last_conv_layer.output])
    model_out, last_conv_layer = iterate(x)
    class_out = model_out[:, 0]
    grads = tape.gradient(class_out, last_conv_layer)
    pooled_grads = K.mean(grads, axis=(0, 1, 2))
  
  heatmap = tf.reduce_mean(tf.multiply(pooled_grads, last_conv_layer), axis=-1)
  heatmap = np.maximum(heatmap, 0)
  heatmap /= np.max(heatmap)
  heatmap = heatmap.reshape((4, 4))
  return heatmap

def build_model_4_1():
  conv_base = VGG16(weights='imagenet', include_top=False, input_shape=(32,32,3))
  #freeze all layers but the last 3 convolutional ones.
  for layer in conv_base.layers:
    if layer.name in ['block5_conv1', 'block5_conv2', 'block5_conv3'] :
        layer.trainable = True
    else:
        layer.trainable = False

  learning_rate = 0.01
  model = models.Sequential()
  model.add(conv_base)
  model.add(layers.Flatten())

  model.add(layers.Dense(375, kernel_regularizer=regularizers.l2(0.001), activation='relu'))
  model.add(layers.Dense(10, activation='softmax'))
  model.compile(optimizer=optimizers.Adagrad(lr=learning_rate),loss='categorical_crossentropy',metrics=['accuracy'])
  return model
